The [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] was the 17th edition of the [[FIFA World Cup]], an international [[association football]] competition that serves as the championship for [[List of men's national association football teams|men's national teams]]. It was held in [[Japan]] and [[South Korea]] from 31 May to 30 June and was contested by 32 teams.<ref>{{cite news |last=Longman |first=Jere |date=31 May 2002 |title=New Location, But Favorites Are Familiar |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/31/sports/soccer-new-location-but-favorites-are-familiar.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |url-access=limited |accessdate=1 November 2024}}</ref> Each national association was required to name a provisional squad of 23 players, expanded from 22 in previous tournaments,{{cn|date=November 2024}} by 21 May 2002.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brodkin |first=Jon |date=13 April 2002 |title=Fifa bends rules for Beckham |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/apr/13/worldcupfootball2002.sport1 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=1 November 2024}}</ref>

The players' ages, [[Cap (association football)|caps]] and clubs are listed as of 31 May 2002, the opening day of the tournament. The oldest player was defender [[Jan Heintze]] of [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] at 38 years, 293 days old; the youngest was [[Femi Opabunmi]], a 17-year-old midfielder for [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Manaschev |first=Erlan |date=3 July 2008 |title=World Cup 2002 - Match Details |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/2002full.html |publisher=[[RSSSF]] |accessdate=1 November 2024}}</ref>

